Your question is vague, but what you probably need is a [computed property][1]. Vue will automatically detect the dependencies of computed properties. For example, there is no need to be explicit here:

```
new Vue({
  data() {
    return {
      firstName: &#39;John&#39;,
      lastName: &#39;Doe&#39;,
    }
  },
  computed: {
    fullName() {
      return `${ firstName } ${ lastName }`;
    }
  }
})
```
Any time `firstName` or `lastName` changes, the computed property `fullName` will also be re-evaluated.


  [1]: https://vuejs.org/v2/guide/computed.html

Sounds like you&#39;re talking about [_watchers_][1]. For example

``` js
data: () =&gt; ({
  dataValName: &#39;a&#39;,
  someOtherDataVal: &#39;b&#39;
}),
watch: {
  someOtherDataVal (newValue) {
    this.dataValName = &#39;c&#39; // or whatever
  }
}
```

Keep in mind, computed properties are almost always a better option.

  [1]: https://it.vuejs.org/v2/guide/computed.html#Watchers

