You&#39;re not using the async generator correctly, but before we get to that, let&#39;s clean up the implementation slightly:

    async function* paginated_generator(source, opts = {}) {
        let buffer = await source(opts)

        while (true) {
            yield * buffer.items

            if (!buffer.paging.next) return

            buffer = await source({ ...opts, next: buffer.paging.next })
        }
    }

When you call an async generator function, it returns an async generator object, which implements both the async iterator and async iterable protocols.

There are a few differences between the syntax and protocols of asynchronous and synchronous counterparts for generator functions and iteration protocols:

* The `next()` method of the [async iterator protocol](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/for-await...of#Iterating_over_async_generators) returns `Promise&lt;{ value: T, done: boolean }&gt;` while the [iterator protocol](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Iteration_protocols#The_iterator_protocol) just returns `{ value: T, done: boolean }`.
* Async iterables use the [`Symbol.asyncIterator`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Symbol/asyncIterator) method instead of the [`Symbol.iterator`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Symbol/iterator) method.
* Async iterables can be consumed with [`for await...of`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/for-await...of) instead of [`for...of`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/for...of).

Here&#39;s how your usage (probably) should look, based on the context you&#39;ve provided:

    const Notification = require(&#39;./Notification&#39;)

    async* notifications_paginated (opts = {}) {
        const instance = this || opts.instance
        const gen = paginated_data(`${instance.api}/news/my`, {
            limit: opts.limit || instance.paginated_size,
            key: &#39;news&#39;,
            prev: opts.prev,
            next: opts.next,
            headers: instance.headers
        })

        for await (const item of gen) {
            yield new Notification(item)
        }
    }

You can then consume your `notifications_paginated()` as an async iterable or async iterator of `Notification` objects.

If you were to attempt to buffer all the items in `notifications_paginated()` before returning, then your API might as well not use pagination at all since buffering the items defeats the purpose of paginating in the first place.

